solution.p:
We use the Concave mirror equation to solve for q. 

	 \frac{1}{q} \amp = \frac{1}{f} - \frac{1}{p}
	 \frac{1}{q} \amp = \frac{1}{10/2} - \frac{1}{20} = \frac{3}{20}

Inverting and putting the units back in, we get

	q = \frac{20}{3}\text{ cm}.

We use the Concave mirror equation to solve for q. 

	 \frac{1}{q} \amp = \frac{1}{f} - \frac{1}{p}
	 \frac{1}{q} \amp = \frac{1}{10/2} - \frac{1}{2} = -\frac{3}{10}

Inverting and putting the units back in, we get

	q = -\frac{10}{3}\text{ cm}.

In the case of real image forming in front of the mirror, q was positive. Now, we get a negative q. The image here will form behind the mirror at a distance \frac{10}{3}\text{ cm}.

We use the convex mirror equation to solve for q. We note that f = -R/2 = -10/2 = -5\text{ cm} here.

	 \frac{1}{q} \amp = \frac{1}{f} - \frac{1}{p}
	 \frac{1}{q} \amp = -\frac{1}{5} - \frac{1}{20} = -\frac{1}{5}

Inverting and putting the units back in, we get

	q = -5\text{ cm}.

The negative sign is expected for convex mirror since the image is behind the mirror. The image will be 5\text{ cm} from the vertex behind the mirror.
